def: 3d pers. sing. pres. of Tread, for treadeth. Chaucer.
To indue or imbue (a body) with soul. [R.] Emerson.

Want of power to produce the desired or proper effect;inefficiency; ineffectualness; futility; uselessness; fruitlessness;as, the inefficacy of medicines or means.The seeming inefficacy of censures. Bp. Hall.The inefficacy was soon proved, like that of many similar medicines.James Gregory.
Pertaining to, or including, similar forms or kinds of life;as, homoeozoic belts on the earth's surface. E. Forbes.
A hold in which the agressor bends back his opponent's foot.
A nitrogenous substance, C8H7NO, isomeric with oxindol,obtained as an oily liquid.
An arch, or ceiling, of boards, placed over the men's heads ina mine.
A master of assay; one who tries or proves. [Obs.] "Greatsaymaster of state." D. Jonson.
